 <td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" valign="top">
  This interactive example allows the creation of a polygon of atoms and
  the calculation of the corresponding Fourier transform. All atoms
  have a distance of r=1.4&Aring; from the origin. This example will 
  illustrate the relation between symmetry of the atomic arrangement 
  and the corresponding scattering pattern. 
  
  <p><hr><p><center>
     <h2><a href="/cgi-bin/legacy/teaching/discus2.cgi?script=teach_poly" target="_blank">Start Simulator</a></h2>
  </center><hr><p>
  
  Play around with different input parameters and answer the following 
  questions:<p>
  <ul>
    <li>Describe the relationship your observe between the symmetry of 
        the atom positions and the symmetry of the resulting diffraction
        pattern ?<p></li>
    <li>What is special about the values <i>n=1,2,3,4</i> and 
        <i>6</i> compared to other values of <i>n</i> ?<p></li>
    <li>What difference do you observe between neutron and x-ray
        diffraction patterns ?<p></li>
  </ul>
  <p><font color="#000099">Once you are done, click <a href="ibasic_r.html">
  here</a> to verify your answers.</font>
  </td>
